Meta-analysis physiological costs of hibernation: Report 5 - Arousal Immune parameters

Pablo Capilla-Lasheras

2025-01-29

This R Markdown Notebook contains the initial meta-analysis for the project ‘physiological ’costs’ of hibernation.

Dataset and calculation of effect sizes

The dataset for this meta-analysis has been collected after a literature search by Pablo Burraco, Marko Prokic and Tamara Petrovic. It contains data on physiological effects of hibernation in different systems. Here a quick snapshot of the first lines of the dataset:

As a summary of the initial dataset:

  • Number of studies: 20
  • Number of species: 12

For this meta-analysis, I am going to include all immune (IM) markers and calculate the standarised mean difference (g) as the effect size of analysis comparing arousal versus euthermia. Positive SMD_arousal values indicate higher IM values in arousal while negative SMD_arousal indicate lower IM values in arousal This is a summary of the effect size calculation based on the dataset above:

Summary of SMD_arousal effect size and number of observations included in the meta-analysis:

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -4.8729 -1.0977 -0.2421 -0.3971  0.3001  3.3649
  • Number of observation with non-missing SMD_arousal: 194
  • Number of studies in the dataset for analysis: 12
  • Number of species in the dataset for analysis: 6

Initial meta-analysis:

This initial model contains only the intercept and five random effects to account for variation between between classes, families, species, between studies and within studies beyond sampling variance.

model_SMD_arousal <- rma.mv(yi = SMD_arousal, 
                     V = SMD.sv_arousal, 
                     mods = ~ 1, 
                     random = list(~1|Study_ID,
                                   ~1|Class,
                                   ~1|Family,
                                   ~1|Species,
                                   ~1|obsID),
                     data=df_SMD_arousal, 
                     method="REML")
